Premier League Transfer Data

Introduction

Are you a big soccer (or should we say football) fan? If you are, then you probably have heard of the most prevalent league in the world, the English Premier League! The league houses 20 competitive teams where the bottom three teams are regulated each season and the three best teams from one league below come up to test their skills and claim a spot for years to come. The most important aspect of these teams are of course, their players, whom the clubs are required to purchase from other clubs, crafting a strategic and cohesive line-up for each game! Through the wonderful R language, we will be exploring how more money spent by a club affects their ability to secure wins. Our data comes from the past 3 seasons of the Premier League! To learn more about the English Premier League and their transfer market, visit. https://www.transfermarkt.co.uk/premier-league/fuenfjahresvergleich/wettbewerb/GB1 https://www.transferleague.co.uk/ https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2016%E2%80%9317_Premier_League https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2017%E2%80%9318_Premier_League https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2018%E2%80%9319_Premier_League

1. Gathering and Loading Data

Step one of the data pipeline starts here. Data scientists such as ourselves should not fret over not having a data set from an excel document or a csv file because we have the entire world wide web as our resource! To get data from the internet, we perform HTML scraping on webpages with tables of data at our disposal. HTML scraping is the process of taking pre-existing data from imbedded tables off of HTML webpages and copying them to our RStudio environment!

url2016 <- "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2016%E2%80%9317_Premier_League"
df_2016 <- read_html(url2016) %>% 
        html_nodes(".wikitable") %>% 
        extract2(4) %>%
        html_table() %>% 
      as.data.frame()

2. Tidying Data

Now that we have all of our data from the webpages, we must tidy it! Tidying data is the process of structuring a dataset so that it is easier to manipulate. When manipulating a tidy dataset, we are analyzing its contents by performing operations such as making new columns for mean and standard deviation, and standardization! Another form of manipulation is changing the individual values of certain columns to allow us to perform these operations. To implement this, we took out the ‘m’ character and the euro character from the columns involving spending of money.

## We have to tidy our data, match our names so we can join and add teams to the transfer dataset that were previously not there

names <- c("Chelsea", "Tottenham Hotspur", "Manchester City", "Liverpool", "Arsenal", "Manchester United", "Everton", "Southampton", "Bournemouth", "West Bromwich Albion", "West Ham United", "Leicester City", "Stoke City", "Crystal Palace", "Swansea City", "Burnley", "Watford", "Hull City", "Middlesbrough", "Sunderland" )

Looking good! Just a note, the column of each dataset pertaining to the particular season should be interpreted as net money spent! So if a team has say, -4.36 million euros, that means that they have spent more than they’ve earned from player transfers.

3. Exploratory Data Analysis

Now that we have our completely tidy datasets, it’s time to begin our analysis of the information throughout the datasets through manipulatory operations. We will perform this with some statistical measures and data visualization.

First let’s take a look at the mean and standard deviations!

## mean
mean16 <- mean(df_2016$NetIncome)
mean17 <- mean(df_2017$NetIncome)
mean18 <- mean(df_2018$NetIncome)

mean16
## [1] -32.59
mean17
## [1] -37.668
mean18
## [1] -50.1565

Ok, so now we have the mean NET TRANSFER INCOME for the premier league from years 2016-2018 (in millions). What does this mean? The net transfer income indicates how much money a club made by just buying and selling players. From the data you can see that on average, each team significantly spent more money than they made through trading players, hence the negative values.

std16 <- sd(df_2016$NetIncome)
std17 <- sd(df_2017$NetIncome)
std18 <- sd(df_2018$NetIncome)

std16
## [1] 44.57684
std17
## [1] 54.3744
std18
## [1] 41.1132

Comparing the standard deviation to the mean, you can see that the distribution of our NET TRANSFER INCOME is very spread out.

3.1 Data Transformation

standardized16 <- df_2016 %>%
  mutate(mean_score = mean(df_2016$NetIncome)) %>%
  mutate(sd_aff = sd(df_2016$NetIncome)) %>%
  mutate(z_aff = (df_2016$NetIncome-mean_score) / sd_aff)
mean16_std <- mean(standardized16$z_aff)
mean16_std
## [1] 8.122978e-17
standardized17 <- df_2017 %>%
  mutate(mean_score = mean(df_2017$NetIncome)) %>%
  mutate(sd_aff = sd(df_2017$NetIncome)) %>%
  mutate(z_aff = (df_2017$NetIncome-mean_score) / sd_aff)
mean17_std <- mean(standardized17$z_aff)
mean17_std
## [1] -2.009772e-17
standardized18 <- df_2018 %>%
  mutate(mean_score = mean(df_2018$NetIncome)) %>%
  mutate(sd_aff = sd(df_2018$NetIncome)) %>%
  mutate(z_aff = (df_2018$NetIncome-mean_score) / sd_aff)
mean18_std <- mean(standardized18$z_aff)
mean18_std
## [1] -9.008365e-18

We standardize our data in order to be able to compare to points easier. Realistically, these values should be 0 but are close enough where we should not see any error coming from them.

4. Machine Learning

4.1 Creating a model

First when trying to evaluate how a team accumulates the most points while racing for the title victory, we need to create a linear model! For our model, we are using wins, goal differential (goals allowed subtracted from goals scored), and Income spent \[ TotalLeaguePoints = \beta_0 + \beta_1*Wins + \beta_2*(GoalsScored - GoalsAllowed) + \beta_3*NetIncome \] ### 4.2 Hypothesis Testing From the chart below, we are able to determine which factors have the greatest effect on Total Points in the League. We made three charts, one from each season, in order to determine consistency in our data. In order to reject the null hypothesis, the p-value for the individual categories must be below our alpha value of 0.05. When we reject the null hypothesis, that means that the specific factor does have an effect on accumulating more points in the league. As you can see from the charts, Wins and Goal Differential are consistently below 0.05, therefore we can reject the null hypothesis for those factors as wins and scoring goals will make a team go ahead in the table. However, in the 2016/17 and 2017/18 seasons, we cannot reject the null hypothesis as spending caused an increase in table spots for teams who spent more!

fit1 <- lm(df_2016$Pts ~ 1 + W + GD + NetIncome, data=df_2016)
broom::tidy(fit1) %>%
  knitr::kable()

4.3 Plotting Correctness/Falsehood of our Model

Now we will compare graphs of fitted values vs residuals to see how accurate our assumptions were from the hypothesis testing! By doing this, we will figure out how far off our model was from the actual data point. Below, you can see that for 2016, the residuals are around 0, and for the 2017 and 2018 seasons, the residuals are a tiny bit above and below 0, respectively. With the high frequencies around zero, we believe that our hypothesis is correct and that even though wins and goals scored have an effect on total points, spending money on players corrolates to accumulation of league points!

augmented_data1 <- fit1 %>%
  augment() %>%
  select(-.se.fit, -.hat, -.sigma, -.cooksd, -.std.resid)
augmented_data1 %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=.fitted, y=.resid)) +
    geom_violin()

augmented_data2 <- fit2 %>%
  augment() %>%
  select(-.se.fit, -.hat, -.sigma, -.cooksd, -.std.resid)
augmented_data2 %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=.fitted, y=.resid)) +
    geom_violin()

augmented_data3 <- fit3 %>%
